# Xiaojie — Diamond Like You
## Critique by Josh Murr, 01-02-20

Looking at oneself in the mirror is part of the daily routine for many people. Whether with intention to put on make up or shave; or through lack of choice in a public bathroom where your floor-to-ceiling self is presented to you; or even just from reflection in a bus window. Regardless, it's hard not to be aware of how you look every day. Advertising has presented us with perfect humans to strive towards, and social media has given us (or every one else it seems) an outlet to show all our peers how perfect our lives are, so now the person to compare yourself against is the person you share the commute with. It is this comparison-culture which Xiaojie has chosen to intervene with in her project 'Diamond Like You'.

Her device is a so called 'fuzzy mirror' - a relatively new phenomena which has grown into it's own category in recent years as technology proliferates through the art world and interaction becomes an art form in itself. A fuzzy mirror typically provides the user with a reflection of themselves, mediated through an alternative material; there is instant feedback and a direct correlation with real-life, but it is not at all a mirror as we know them. Xiaojie's piece is made up of hexagonal modules, covering approximately half a square metre, covered in meticulously placed icey-blue gems. The hexagonal units light up LEDs behind the gems and play squeaky but endearing sounds as movement is detected. 

Xiaojie's mirror only works at a distance, which is an intentional feature forcing the user to step back - in fact she refers to this as the 'art of step-back'. This notion does resonate with me, and I believe most meaningful artworks do make you step back (physically or metaphorically) — I'm not sure however if an artist can force this interaction deliberately and acheive the same results. Xiaojie is trying to make the user rethink how they interact with their own reflection. The title 'Diamond Like You' is an unsubtle reference to self-worth, which for many people is something they struggle with daily. I am not convinced that that the novel interactions brought about in fuzzy-mirrors or similar artworks are the way to deliver such a delicate message however. The literal connection between reflection and self-worth lacks the beauty of metaphor. Alva Noë suggests the general form of the artwork is: _See me if you can!_ It is in this conundrum that true revelatory artworks hold power; those who find meaning in the artwork are the ones rewarded with some personal growth. Xiaojie is on an interesting path if she chooses to continue to tackle such real problems in her work, but I think in this particular work the endearing interaction, and literal metaphors smother the true meaning of the piece.

The artwork is by-and-large a prototype as Xiaojie's says herself that the original plan was for it to be much larger. I would love to see that happen as the attention to detail on a huge scale could change the piece entirely, but we can only speculate. She is keen to explore this interactive mechanic as she refers to the work of Daniel Rosin as an inspiration of hers. Rosin is an aficionado in the world of fuzzy-mirrors and has a whole catalogue of works in that category. Key to Rosin's work are the modest titles such as 'Trash Mirror', 'Shiny Balls Mirror' or 'Wooden Mirror', which allow the simple interaction between the reflection and user to be the defining feature of the work. Personally I really appreciate when an artist is honest about their motives and I worry that Xiaojie's work loses it's ability to become something playful and beautifully simple by attempting to take on such personal issues. 

These kinds of interactive pieces rely on the ubiquity of cheap and accessible programmable micro-controllers, servo motors, colour changing LEDs and so on. But technology in art is a difficult practice to manage. Noë offers even more insight when he says 'technology is no contribution to art; it is its precondition.' Noë is referring to all technologies here, including paintbrush and canvas, but his words hold even more impact now where all too often we see artworks which at their core are just technological smoke and mirrors. Or as Alan Warburton says, 'interactive tech-art is great content, but somehow lacks content.'

I have had the privilege of hearing Xiaojie speak about another topic which interests here: Design Thinking. Design Thinking is the broad term which attempts to encapsulate such buzzwords as __context analysis, creative thinking, solution generating__ and so on. Xiaojie is interested in breaking this process apart and revealing that it is not that easy to compartmentalise such an abstract idea. She wants to inject some crtitical thinking into the process encouraging designers to consider their own approach to the design pipeline, and the impact their decisions have throughout the process and beyond. I can see that she is on the right tracks to create meaningful work and is asking interesting interrogative questions. I am excited to see her use of technology, drive to consider her own methodoliges and interest in user interaction combine in future work. The potential to make true moments of reflection are certainly within reach.
